SIMPLE: priory
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Priory
<hw>Pri"o*ry</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it>
<plw>Priories</plw> <pr>(#)</pr>.</plu> <ety>[Cf. LL.
<ets>prioria</ets>. See <er>Prior</er>, <pos>n.</pos>]</ety> <def>A
religious house presided over by a prior or prioress; -- sometimes an
offshoot of, an subordinate to, an abbey, and called also
<altname>cell</altname>, and <altname>obedience</altname>. See
<er>Cell</er>, 2.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ Of such houses there were two sorts: one where the prior
was chosen by the inmates, and governed as independently as an abbot in
an abbey; the other where the priory was subordinate to an abbey, and
the prior was placed or displaced at the will of the abbot.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Alien priory</b></col>, <cd>a small religious house
dependent on a large monastery in some other country.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- See <er>Cloister</er>.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Pris</ent>⟦br⟧
